ğŸ’¡ Core OOP Concepts

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) revolves around real-world objects having data and behavior.

ğŸ”¹ Class

A blueprint for creating objects.
â¡ï¸ Example: Car class with attributes like color, and methods like drive().

ğŸ”¹ Object

An instance of a class.
â¡ï¸ Example: A red Ferrari is an object of the Car class.

ğŸ”¹ Inheritance

Deriving new classes from existing ones (code reuse).
â¡ï¸ Example: Truck, Car, and Bike inherit from Vehicle.

ğŸ”¹ Polymorphism

Performing a single action in multiple ways.

Method Overloading ğŸ” (Compile-time): Multiple methods with the same name, different parameters.

Method Overriding ğŸ” (Run-time): Subclass modifies a superclass method.


ğŸ”¹ Abstraction

Hide internal complexity; show only essentials.
â¡ï¸ Like using a TV remote without knowing the circuitry.

ğŸ”¹ Encapsulation

Bundle data and code into a single unit (class).
â¡ï¸ Use private variables and public getter/setter methods.


---

âš”ï¸ OOP vs POP

ğŸ§© Aspect	ğŸ§± OOP (Object-Oriented)	âš™ï¸ POP (Procedural-Oriented)

Approach	Bottom-up	Top-down
Focus	Objects & Data	Functions & Procedures
Program Division	Into classes & objects	Into functions
Data Sharing	Restricted (Encapsulation)	Freely shared
Security	High	Low
Examples	Java, C++, Python	C, Pascal, FORTRAN



